Differential diagnosis
. Overall body shape and colour similar to others in the genus. Most common colour morph is richly green (
Fig. 1A
, 
2A
) with tegmen bearing a few small black spots (
Fig. 4B
). Eyes often purple or lavender in life. Ventral surface of abdomen and thorax bright yellow; intersegmental membrane with small, irregular purple markings (
Fig. 4D
). Rarely, in less than 10% of population (speculative) a golden or yellow morph is encountered, (
Fig. 3A, B
) the markings on the ventral surface of the Gold Morph are as described above. Scape, pedicel and flagellum of antenna uniformly green (
Fig. 4A
). Male cercus species distinctive (
Figs 5A, B
); titillators distinctive with tips usually hooked (
Fig. 4F
). Females have distinctive subgenital plate and the ovipositor is half the length or less than the hind femur, strongly falcate, the margins unarmed (
Fig. 4E
).

Head.
Head produced well in front of pronotum, frons relatively flat, not punctate (
Fig. 4A
). Frontal fastigium absent; fastigium of vertex short, stout, extending only to middle of scape, surface smooth, not sulcate (
Fig. 2A
). Eye prominent, positioned high on head, round. Median ocellus small, irregular; lateral ocelli absent. Antenna with scape relatively short, produced on internal margin; pedicel about 1/3 length of scape; flagellum 1.5–2.0x body length.

Wings.
Tegmen elongate, of nearly equal width throughout, apex obtuse. Tegminal venation (
Fig. 4B
) with costal area well defined, costa absent; stridulatory area rather small, stridulatory vein poorly defined in dorsal view, mirror roughly quadrate, without internal venation (
Fig. 4C
); stridulatory file (
Fig. 5C
) with teeth lamellar. Wing very well developed, capable of flight (
Figs 1A
, 
3A, B
).

Abdomen.
Tenth tergite with shallow, membranous median incision. Cercus (
Figs 5A, B
) with internal tooth concealed in dorsal view, apex subacute, internal margin undulating; internal surface revealing a short, stout tooth, outer margin weakly indented. Phallic complex (
Fig. 4F
) with arms flattened, with a subapical hook on internal surface; base minutely stippled. Subgenital plate (
Fig. 4D
) short, broad, with deep V-shaped median incision; styles very elongate, length of median incision.

Female.
Differs from male in following characters. Size larger, form slightly more robust. Subgenital plate (
Fig. 4F
) with V-shaped median incision, lateral portions strongly acute. Ovipositor (
Fig. 1A
) falcate, strongly upcurved, about length of hind femur, unarmed.

Differential diagnosis.
Overall body shape similar to others in the genus; dominant colour grey with greenish tinges. Tegmen greyish brown with large quadrate spots (
Fig. 7A
). Eyes (
Fig. 6C
). Ventral surface of abdomen distinctive marked with grey and black (
Fig. 6D
); abdominal intersegmental membrane indistinct. Median ocellus small, ovoid; lateral ocelli absent. Male cercus distinctive, with prominent internal tooth (
Figs 7B, C
); titillators (
Fig. 6G
) Female abdomen with 8, 9 sternites with large tubercles; subgenital plate short, arms elongate (
Fig. 7D
).

Wings.
Tegmen of male short, stout (
Fig. 6A
) of female more elongate. Tegminal venation (
Fig. 7A
) with costal area well defined, costa absent; stridulatory area rather poorly defined, stridulatory vein rather thin, mirror quadrate, lacking internal venation; stridulatory file with teeth lamellar. Wing well developed, individuals fully capable of flight.

Abdomen.
Tenth tergite with shallow, broadly U-shaped median incision. Cercus (
Figs 7B, C
) with internal tooth prominent, elongate, with apical hook directed upwards, fully visible from above, apex acute. Base of titllators with membranous portion weakly tuberculate lateral membranous portions very weakly sclerotised, forming distinct swellings (
Fig. 6G
). Subgenital plate relatively elongate, distinctly scoop-shaped, with deep V-shaped median incision, styles very elongate, about as long as one side of median incision.

Coloration.
General coloration of this species is more variable than in other 

Austrosalomona

. Ventral surface with distinctive black markings on thorax and abdomen (
Fig. 6F
). Some specimens have mottled green on legs and thorax (
Fig. 6A
) whilst others are uniformly mottled grey and show no trace of greenish coloration (
Fig. 6B
).
